ndly\" and \"eats unhealthily\". No explicit teamwork but leadership.\n\nCandidate B:\n- Very conscientious (reliability)\n- Handles stress very well (calmness)\n- Good at assessing weather conditions (technical)\n- Excellent computer skills (technical)\n- Regarded as pretentious (attitude)\n- Sometimes adopts wrong tone when communicating (communication)\n- Also earlier \"makes nasty remarks about his colleagues\" (maybe not in list but appears in some earlier? Not in given list but maybe from other agent? Not in our knowledge; we have only pretentious and wrong tone.)\n- No explicit teamwork.\n\nCandidate C:\n- Makes correct decisions quickly (decision-making)\n- Difficulty communicating ideas (communication weakness)\n- Regarded as egocentric (teamwork)\n- Not very willing to further his education (development)\n- 100% reliable (reliability)\n- Creates positive atmosphere with his crew (teamwork/crew cooperation)\n- Keeps calm in a crisis (calmness)\n- Understands complicated technology (technical)\n- No health issues.\n\nCandidate D:\n- Responds to unexpected events adequately (calmness)\n- Concentrates very well (cognitive)\n- Solves problems extremely well (technical/problem solving)\n- Takes responsibility seriously (reliability)\n- Considered moody (communication/teamwork)\n- Regarded as a loner (teamwork)\n- Weak leadership skills (leadership)\n- Arrogant (attitude)\n- No health issues.\n\nNow evaluate criteria:\n\nReliability/responsibility: C (100% reliable), D (takes responsibility seriously), B (very conscientious), A (anticipates dangerous situations but unorganized, health concerns). So C highest.\n\nTechnical/cognitive competence: A (spatial vision, complex connections), B (weather assessment, computer), C (understands complicated tech), D (problem solving, concentration). All decent. A maybe strongest for navigation.\n\nCalmness/judgment under pressure: C (keeps calm in crisis), B (handles stress well), D (responds adequately), A (anticipates dangerous situations maybe proactive). C strongest.\n\nDecision-making: C (quick correct decisions), D (problem solving), A (anticipates dangerous situations), B (weather assessment). C strongest.\n\nTeamwork/communication: C creates positive atmosphere but difficulty communicating, egocentric. B pretentious, wrong tone. D loner, moody, weak leadership. A unfriendly, not good at criticism, unorganized. So all have issues, but C has positive crew atmosphere, which is a strong indicator of teamwork. B and D have negative interpersonal traits. A also negative.\n\nProfessional development: C not willing to further education (negative). B no mention of development but has computer skills. D weak leadership, no mention of development. A health concerns.\n\nOverall, C seems best despite communication and development concerns because reliability, calmness, decision-making, and crew atmosphere are critical for long-distance flights. The communication issues could be mitigated with training, but the core safety attributes are strong.\n\nThus I will vote for Candidate C.\n\nWe should also note any uncertainties: C's egocentric and communication difficulty could affect crew coordination, but positive atmosphere suggests he manages. Also his unwillingness to further education could be a risk for staying current with regulations. However other candidates have more severe interpersonal deficits.\n\nThus vote C.\n\nNow produce public message: Summarize reasoning, note that we have no additional info beyond what's listed, and state vote."}
